INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '25d06c8a-6660-4808-bcc6-3efdf7d6c343',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$TensorFlow Model Serialization — SavedModel vs. Keras H5 vs. Weights-Only$escape$,
  $escape$TensorFlow offers three primary serialization strategies, each with distinct trade-offs. The `SavedModel` format (default since TF 2.0) is the production standard — it exports the full computation graph, variables, and serving signatures, making it portable across TF Serving, TF Lite, and TF.js without needing the original Python class definition. Use `model.save('path/to/dir')` to produce it.

Keras `.h5` is legacy but still common for research. It bundles architecture + weights in one file, but struggles with custom layers and non-sequential topologies. Avoid it for anything you'll deploy.

For training resumption, checkpointing with `tf.train.Checkpoint` is more granular than full serialization — it saves optimizer state, step count, and arbitrary variables. Pair it with `tf.train.CheckpointManager` to retain only the last N checkpoints and auto-restore the latest.

Weights-only serialization via `model.save_weights()` / `model.load_weights()` is fastest for fine-tuning workflows where architecture is fixed in code. Use `save_format='tf'` (default) over `'h5'` for checkpoint-style sharding on large models.$escape$,
  $escape$import tensorflow as tf

model = tf.keras.Sequential([tf.keras.layers.Dense(64, activation='relu'), tf.keras.layers.Dense(10)])
model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy')

# SavedModel (recommended for serving)
model.save('saved_model/my_model')
restored = tf.keras.models.load_model('saved_model/my_model')

# Checkpoint with manager (recommended for training)
ckpt = tf.train.Checkpoint(model=model, optimizer=model.optimizer)
manager = tf.train.CheckpointManager(ckpt, './ckpts', max_to_keep=3)
manager.save()
ckpt.restore(manager.latest_checkpoint).expect_partial()$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
